<div class="highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>Significant work has shown that indiciduals change their behaviorï¼ˆä¸ªä½“æ”¹å˜è¡Œä¸ºï¼‰ through explicit peer influenceï¼ˆåŒä¼´å½±å“ï¼‰ and implicitly observing their peers' actionsï¼ˆè§‚å¯Ÿåˆ°åŒä¼´çš„è¡Œä¸ºï¼‰.For example,the effects of explicit ties within a social network have been shown to manifest in a number of social phenomena such as information diffusion [9,16], peer influence[74], and exercise frequency [3,6].
</code></pre></div></div>
<div class="highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>Similarly, other work has examined communities as a wholeï¼ˆä½œä¸ºä¸€ä¸ªæ•´ä½“ï¼‰, showing their potential influence on behavioral aspectsï¼ˆè¡Œä¸ºæ–¹é¢çš„æ½œåœ¨å½±å“ï¼‰ such as linguistic norms [24], visual presentation [84], and content moderation [51]. 
